An attempt to be goodfellas but instead of bringing us in with shine and excitement, we go right into the violence. Has some interesting examinations of how a creation can get out of control, but it starts you at too far a distance to truly feel that downfall.

Perfectly builds an unanswerable mystery, giving you dual answers without feeling manipulative. Without it feeling like subjective pov, it gives you all the facts and lets you answer. While also giving the subjectivity of each character.

A great anti-genre horror thriller. Doesn’t reach the heights of Altman, but I love the build up of the violence that just leads to them burning it all down.

Carries the emotion and enormity of the march and Rustin’s influence in an expert manner. Its quick flashy style does get jarring at times, but helps get to the characters and who they are very quickly. And the jazz score is *chefs kiss*

Thinking a lot about the structure of this in terms of clues/discovery. Instead of setting up every clue at the beginning, Director Park uses flashbacks to show the clue before quickly going into investigation/discovery. But since we experienced his 15 years, going to the flashback feels earned.
